# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-data-factory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The decision to integrate data tends to arise when the volume, complexity (that is, big data) and need to share existing data explodes.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] It has become the focus of extensive theoretical work, and numerous open problems remain unsolved.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Data integration encourages collaboration between internal as well as external users.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The data being integrated must be received from a heterogeneous database system and transformed to a single coherent data store that provides synchronous data across a network of files for clients.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] A common use of data integration is in data mining when analyzing and extracting information from existing databases that can be useful for Business information.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Issues with combining heterogeneous data sources, often referred to as information silos, under a single query interface have existed for some time.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In the early 1980s, computer scientists began designing systems for interoperability of heterogeneous databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The first data integration system driven by structured metadata was designed in 1991 at the University of Minnesota for the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] IPUMS used a data warehousing approach, which extracts, transforms, and loads data from heterogeneous sources into a unique view schema so data from different sources become compatible.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] By making thousands of population databases interoperable, IPUMS demonstrated the feasibility of large-scale data integration.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The data warehouse approach offers a tightly coupled architecture because the data are already physically reconciled in a single queryable repository, so it usually takes little time to resolve queries.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The data warehouse approach is less feasible for data sets that are frequently updated, requiring the extract, transform, load (ETL) process to be continuously re-executed for synchronization.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Difficulties also arise in constructing data warehouses when one has only a query interface to summary data sources and no access to the full data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This problem frequently emerges when integrating several commercial query services like travel or classified advertisement web applications.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] A trend began in 2009 favoring the loose coupling of data and providing a unified query-interface to access real time data over a mediated schema (see Figure 2), which allows information to be retrieved directly from original databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This is consistent with the SOA approach popular in that era.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This approach relies on mappings between the mediated schema and the schema of original sources, and translating a query into decomposed queries to match the schema of the original databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Such mappings can be specified in two ways: as a mapping from entities in the mediated schema to entities in the original sources (the "Global-as-View" (GAV) approach), or as a mapping from entities in the original sources to the mediated schema (the "Local-as-View" (LAV) approach).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The latter approach requires more sophisticated inferences to resolve a query on the mediated schema, but makes it easier to add new data sources to a (stable) mediated schema.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] As of 2010, some of the work in data integration research concerns the semantic integration problem.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This problem addresses not the structuring of the architecture of the integration, but how to resolve semantic conflicts between heterogeneous data sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] For example, if two companies merge their databases, certain concepts and definitions in their respective schemas like "earnings" inevitably have different meanings.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In one database it may mean profits in dollars (a floating-point number), while in the other it might represent the number of sales (an integer).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] A common strategy for the resolution of such problems involves the use of ontologies which explicitly define schema terms and thus help to resolve semantic conflicts.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This approach represents ontology-based data integration.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] On the other hand, the problem of combining research results from different bioinformatics repositories requires bench-marking of the similarities, computed from different data sources, on a single criterion such as positive predictive value.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This enables the data sources to be directly comparable and can be integrated even when the natures of experiments are distinct.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] As of 2011, it was determined that current data modeling methods were imparting data isolation into every data architecture in the form of islands of disparate data and information silos.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This data isolation is an unintended artifact of the data modeling methodology that results in the development of disparate data models.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Disparate data models, when instantiated as databases, form disparate databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Enhanced data model methodologies have been developed to eliminate the data isolation artifact and to promote the development of integrated data models.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] One enhanced data modeling method recasts data models by augmenting them with structural metadata in the form of standardized data entities.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] As a result of recasting multiple data models, the set of recast data models will now share one or more commonality relationships that relate the structural metadata now common to these data models.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Commonality relationships are a peer-to-peer type of entity relationships that relate the standardized data entities of multiple data models.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Multiple data models that contain the same standard data entity may participate in the same commonality relationship.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] When integrated data models are instantiated as databases and are properly populated from a common set of master data, then these databases are integrated.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Since 2011, data hub approaches have been of greater interest than fully structured (typically relational) Enterprise Data Warehouses.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Since 2013, data lake approaches have risen to the level of Data Hubs.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] (See all three search terms popularity on Google Trends.) These approaches combine unstructured or varied data into one location, but do not necessarily require an (often complex) master relational schema to structure and define all data in the Hub.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Data integration plays a big role in business regarding data collection used for studying the market.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Converting the raw data retrieved from consumers into coherent data is something businesses try to do when considering what steps they should take next.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Organizations are more frequently using data mining for collecting information and patterns from their databases, and this process helps them develop new business strategies to increase business performance and perform economic analyses more efficiently.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Compiling the large amount of data they collect to be stored in their system is a form of data integration adapted for Business intelligence to improve their chances of success.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Consider a web application where a user can query a variety of information about cities (such as crime statistics, weather, hotels, demographics, etc.).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Traditionally, the information must be stored in a single database with a single schema.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] But any single enterprise would find information of this breadth somewhat difficult and expensive to collect.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Even if the resources exist to gather the data, it would likely duplicate data in existing crime databases, weather websites, and census data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] A data-integration solution may address this problem by considering these external resources as materialized views over a virtual mediated schema, resulting in "virtual data integration".
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This means application-developers construct a virtual schema—the *mediated schema*—to best model the kinds of answers their users want.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Next, they design "wrappers" or adapters for each data source, such as the crime database and weather website.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] These adapters simply transform the local query results (those returned by the respective websites or databases) into an easily processed form for the data integration solution (see figure 2).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] When an application-user queries the mediated schema, the data-integration solution transforms this query into appropriate queries over the respective data sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Finally, the virtual database combines the results of these queries into the answer to the user's query.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This solution offers the convenience of adding new sources by simply constructing an adapter or an application software blade for them.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] It contrasts with ETL systems or with a single database solution, which require manual integration of entire new data set into the system.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The virtual ETL solutions leverage virtual mediated schema to implement data harmonization; whereby the data are copied from the designated "master" source to the defined targets, field by field.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Advanced data virtualization is also built on the concept of object-oriented modeling in order to construct virtual mediated schema or virtual metadata repository, using hub and spoke architecture.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Each data source is disparate and as such is not designed to support reliable joins between data sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Therefore, data virtualization as well as data federation depends upon accidental data commonality to support combining data and information from disparate data sets.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Because of the lack of data value commonality across data sources, the return set may be inaccurate, incomplete, and impossible to validate.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] One solution is to recast disparate databases to integrate these databases without the need for ETL.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The recast databases support commonality constraints where referential integrity may be enforced between databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The recast databases provide designed data access paths with data value commonality across databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The theory of data integration forms a subset of database theory and formalizes the underlying concepts of the problem in first-order logic.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Applying the theories gives indications as to the feasibility and difficulty of data integration.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] While its definitions may appear abstract, they have sufficient generality to accommodate all manner of integration systems, including those that include nested relational / XML databases and those that treat databases as programs.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Connections to particular databases systems such as Oracle or DB2 are provided by implementation-level technologies such as JDBC and are not studied at the theoretical level.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Data integration systems are formally defined as a tuple $\left\langle G,S,M\right\rangle$ where G is the global (or mediated) schema, S is the heterogeneous set of source schemas, and M is the mapping that maps queries between the source and the global schemas.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Both G and S are expressed in languages over alphabets composed of symbols for each of their respective relations.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The mapping M consists of assertions between queries over G and queries over S .
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] When users pose queries over the data integration system, they pose queries over G and the mapping then asserts connections between the elements in the global schema and the source schemas.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] A database over a schema is defined as a set of sets, one for each relation (in a relational database).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The database corresponding to the source schema S would comprise the set of sets of tuples for each of the heterogeneous data sources and is called the *source database*.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Note that this single source database may actually represent a collection of disconnected databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The database corresponding to the virtual mediated schema G is called the *global database*.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The global database must satisfy the mapping M with respect to the source database.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The legality of this mapping depends on the nature of the correspondence between G and S .
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Two popular ways to model this correspondence exist: *Global as View* or GAV and *Local as View* or LAV.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] GAV systems model the global database as a set of views over S .
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of G a query over S .
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Query processing becomes a straightforward operation due to the well-defined associations between G and S .
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The burden of complexity falls on implementing mediator code instructing the data integration system exactly how to retrieve elements from the source databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] If any new sources join the system, considerable effort may be necessary to update the mediator, thus the GAV approach appears preferable when the sources seem unlikely to change.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In a GAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer would first develop mediators for each of the city information sources and then design the global schema around these mediators.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] For example, consider if one of the sources served a weather website.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The designer would likely then add a corresponding element for weather to the global schema.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Then the bulk of effort concentrates on writing the proper mediator code that will transform predicates on weather into a query over the weather website.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This effort can become complex if some other source also relates to weather, because the designer may need to write code to properly combine the results from the two sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] On the other hand, in LAV, the source database is modeled as a set of views over G .
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of S a query over G .
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Here the exact associations between G and S are no longer well-defined.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] As is illustrated in the next section, the burden of determining how to retrieve elements from the sources is placed on the query processor.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The benefit of an LAV modeling is that new sources can be added with far less work than in a GAV system, thus the LAV approach should be favored in cases where the mediated schema is less stable or likely to change.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In an LAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer designs the global schema first and then simply inputs the schemas of the respective city information sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Consider again if one of the sources serves a weather website.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The designer would add corresponding elements for weather to the global schema only if none existed already.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Then programmers write an adapter or wrapper for the website and add a schema description of the website's results to the source schemas.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The complexity of adding the new source moves from the designer to the query processor.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The theory of query processing in data integration systems is commonly expressed using conjunctive queries and Datalog, a purely declarative logic programming language.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] One can loosely think of a conjunctive query as a logical function applied to the relations of a database such as " $f(A,B)$ where $A<B$ ".
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] If a tuple or set of tuples is substituted into the rule and satisfies it (makes it true), then we consider that tuple as part of the set of answers in the query.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] While formal languages like Datalog express these queries concisely and without ambiguity, common SQL queries count as conjunctive queries as well.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In terms of data integration, "query containment" represents an important property of conjunctive queries.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] A query A contains another query B (denoted $A\supset B$ ) if the results of applying B are a subset of the results of applying A for any database.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The two queries are said to be equivalent if the resulting sets are equal for any database.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This is important because in both GAV and LAV systems, a user poses conjunctive queries over a *virtual* schema represented by a set of views, or "materialized" conjunctive queries.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Integration seeks to rewrite the queries represented by the views to make their results equivalent or maximally contained by our user's query.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This corresponds to the problem of answering queries using views (AQUV).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In GAV systems, a system designer writes mediator code to define the query-rewriting.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Each element in the user's query corresponds to a substitution rule just as each element in the global schema corresponds to a query over the source.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Query processing simply expands the subgoals of the user's query according to the rule specified in the mediator and thus the resulting query is likely to be equivalent.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] While the designer does the majority of the work beforehand, some GAV systems such as Tsimmis involve simplifying the mediator description process.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In LAV systems, queries undergo a more radical process of rewriting because no mediator exists to align the user's query with a simple expansion strategy.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The integration system must execute a search over the space of possible queries in order to find the best rewrite.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The resulting rewrite may not be an equivalent query but maximally contained, and the resulting tuples may be incomplete.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] As of 2011 the GQR algorithm is the leading query rewriting algorithm for LAV data integration systems.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] In general, the complexity of query rewriting is NP-complete.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] If the space of rewrites is relatively small, this does not pose a problem — even for integration systems with hundreds of sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] Large-scale questions in science, such as real world evidence, global warming, invasive species spread, and resource depletion, are increasingly requiring the collection of disparate data sets for meta-analysis.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] This type of data integration is especially challenging for ecological and environmental data because metadata standards are not agreed upon and there are many different data types produced in these fields.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] National Science Foundation initiatives such as Datanet are intended to make data integration easier for scientists by providing cyberinfrastructure and setting standards.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The Research Data Alliance, has more recently explored creating global data integration frameworks.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-integration] The OpenPHACTS project, funded through the European Union Innovative Medicines Initiative, built a drug discovery platform by linking datasets from providers such as European Bioinformatics Institute, Royal Society of Chemistry, UniProt, WikiPathways and DrugBank.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] In computing, **data transformation** is the process of converting data from one format or structure into another format or structure.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] It is a fundamental aspect of most data integration and data management tasks such as data wrangling, data warehousing, data integration and application integration.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Data transformation can be simple or complex based on the required changes to the data between the source (initial) data and the target (final) data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Data transformation is typically performed via a mixture of manual and automated steps.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Tools and technologies used for data transformation can vary widely based on the format, structure, complexity, and volume of the data being transformed.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] A master data recast is another form of data transformation where the entire database of data values is transformed or recast without extracting the data from the database.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] All data in a well-designed database is directly or indirectly related to a limited set of master database tables by a network of foreign key constraints.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Each foreign key constraint is dependent upon a unique database index from the parent database table.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Therefore, when the proper master database table is recast with a different unique index, the directly and indirectly related data are also recast or restated.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] The directly and indirectly related data may also still be viewed in the original form since the original unique index still exists with the master data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Also, the database recast must be done in such a way as to not impact the applications architecture software.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] When the data mapping is indirect via a mediating data model, the process is also called **data mediation**.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Data transformation can be divided into the following steps, each applicable as needed based on the complexity of the transformation required.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] These steps are often the focus of developers or technical data analysts who may use multiple specialized tools to perform their tasks.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Traditionally, data transformation has been a bulk or batch process, whereby developers write code or implement transformation rules in a data integration tool, and then execute that code or those rules on large volumes of data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] This process can follow the linear set of steps as described in the data transformation process above.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Batch data transformation is the cornerstone of virtually all data integration technologies such as data warehousing, data migration and application integration.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] When data must be transformed and delivered with low latency, the term "microbatch" is often used.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] This refers to small batches of data (e.g. a small number of rows or a small set of data objects) that can be processed very quickly and delivered to the target system when needed.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Traditional data transformation processes have served companies well for decades.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] The various tools and technologies (data profiling, data visualization, data cleansing, data integration etc.) have matured and most (if not all) enterprises transform enormous volumes of data that feed internal and external applications, data warehouses and other data stores.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] This traditional process also has limitations that hamper its overall efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] The people who need to use the data (e.g. business users) do not play a direct role in the data transformation process.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Typically, users hand over the data transformation task to developers who have the necessary coding or technical skills to define the transformations and execute them on the data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] This process leaves the bulk of the work of defining the required transformations to the developer, which often in turn do not have the same domain knowledge as the business user.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] The developer interprets the business user requirements and implements the related code/logic.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] This has the potential of introducing errors into the process (through misinterpreted requirements), and also increases the time to arrive at a solution.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] This problem has given rise to the need for agility and self-service in data integration (i.e. empowering the user of the data and enabling them to transform the data themselves interactively).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] There are companies that provide self-service data transformation tools.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] They are aiming to efficiently analyze, map and transform large volumes of data without the technical knowledge and process complexity that currently exists.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] While these companies use traditional batch transformation, their tools enable more interactivity for users through visual platforms and easily repeated scripts.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Still, there might be some compatibility issues (e.g. new data sources like IoT may not work correctly with older tools) and compliance limitations due to the difference in data governance, preparation and audit practices.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Although interactive data transformation follows the same data integration process steps as batch data integration, the key difference is that the steps are not necessarily followed in a linear fashion and typically don't require significant technical skills for completion.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] There are a number of companies that provide interactive data transformation tools, including Trifacta, Alteryx and Paxata.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] They are aiming to efficiently analyze, map and transform large volumes of data while at the same time abstracting away some of the technical complexity and processes which take place under the hood.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Interactive data transformation solutions provide an integrated visual interface that combines the previously disparate steps of data analysis, data mapping and code generation/execution and data inspection.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] That is, if changes are made at one step (like for example renaming), the software automatically updates the preceding or following steps accordingly.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Interfaces for interactive data transformation incorporate visualizations to show the user patterns and anomalies in the data so they can identify erroneous or outlying values.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Once they've finished transforming the data, the system can generate executable code/logic, which can be executed or applied to subsequent similar data sets.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] There are numerous languages available for performing data transformation.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Many transformation languages require a grammar to be provided.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] In many cases, the grammar is structured using something closely resembling Backus–Naur form (BNF).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] There are numerous languages available for such purposes varying in their accessibility (cost) and general usefulness.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Additionally, companies such as Trifacta and Paxata have developed domain-specific transformational languages (DSL) for servicing and transforming datasets.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] The development of domain-specific languages has been linked to increased productivity and accessibility for non-technical users.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Trifacta's “Wrangle” is an example of such a domain-specific language.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Another advantage of the recent domain-specific transformational languages trend is that a domain-specific transformational language can abstract the underlying execution of the logic defined in the domain-specific transformational language.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] They can also utilize that same logic in various processing engines, such as Spark, MapReduce, and Dataflow.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] In other words, with a domain-specific transformational language, the transformation language is not tied to the underlying engine.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] Although transformational languages are typically best suited for transformation, something as simple as regular expressions can be used to achieve useful transformation.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] A text editor like vim, emacs or TextPad supports the use of regular expressions with arguments.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] This would allow all instances of a particular pattern to be replaced with another pattern using parts of the original pattern.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-transformation-computing] In other words, all instances of a function invocation of foo with three arguments, followed by a function invocation with two arguments would be replaced with a single function invocation using some or all of the original set of arguments.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:azure-data-factory/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:azure-data-factory/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:azure-data-factory/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:azure-data-factory/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
